/961\u001b[0m \u001b[32m━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\u001b[0m\u001b[37m\u001b[0m \u001b[1m66s\u001b[0m 68ms/step - accuracy: 0.9637 - loss: 0.0920 - val_accuracy: 0.9914 - val_loss: 0.0287 - learning_rate: 1.0000e-04\nEpoch 10/10\n\u001b[1m961/961\u001b[0m \u001b[32m━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\u001b[0m\u001b[37m\u001b[0m \u001b[1m66s\u001b[0m 69ms/step - accuracy: 0.9686 - loss: 0.0805 - val_accuracy: 0.9908 - val_loss: 0.0259 - learning_rate: 1.0000e-04\nPhase 1 training complete\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":7},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 3.3. Phase 1 Evaluation\nTo evaluate our binary model, visualization of the learning curves, the Confusion Matrix, and the ROC-AUC curve.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"print(\"Generating evaluation metrics for phase 1\")\n\n# 1. Predictions\n# Ask the trained model to predict the outcome for every image in the test set\npredictions = model_binary.predict(test_generator)\n\n# Since predictions are raw probabilities(like 0.87), convert them to hard integers:\n# 1 if probability > 50%, otherwise 0\ny_pred = (predictions > 0.5).astype(int).reshape(-1)\n\n# Extract the ground-truth labels from the test generator\ny_true = test_generator.classes\n\n# 2. Setup figure\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(20, 6))\n\n#Plot 1: Learning curves (tracking how the AI improved over time)\naxes[0].plot(history_binary.history['accuracy'], label='Train Acc', marker='o') # Accuracy on training data\naxes[0].plot(history_binary.history['val_accuracy'], label='Val Acc', marker='o') # Accuracy on unseen test data\naxes[0].set_title('Learning Curves (Accuracy)')\naxes[0].set_xlabel('Epochs') # Number of training loops\naxes[0].set_ylabel('Accuracy')\naxes[0].legend()\naxes[0].grid(True)\n\n#Plot 2: Confusion matrix (visualizing where the model made mistakes)\ncm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred) # Calculate true positives, false positives,..\nsns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', ax=axes[1],\n            xticklabels=['Healthy (0)', 'Sick (1)'], \n            yticklabels=['Healthy (0)', 'Sick (1)'])\naxes[1].set_title('Confusion Matrix: Healthy vs Sick')\naxes[1].set_xlabel('Predicted Label') # What the AI guessed\naxes[1].set_ylabel('True Label') # What the real diagnosis is\n\n#Plot 3: ROC curve (measures the model's ability to distinguish between classes at various thresholds)\nfpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_true, predictions) # Calculate false positive rate and true positive rate\nroc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr) # Calculate the area under the curve (1.0 is perfect)\naxes[2].plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=2, label=f'ROC curve (AUC = {roc_auc:.2f})')\n# Draw the diagonal line of randomness (dashed line), a model must be above this line\naxes[2].plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')\naxes[2].set_xlim([0.0, 1.0])\naxes[2].set_ylim([0.0, 1.05])\naxes[2].set_xlabel('False Positive Rate')\naxes[2].set_ylabel('True Positive Rate')\naxes[2].set_title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC)')\naxes[2].legend(loc=\"lower right\")\n\nplt.tight_layout() # Prevent overlapping text\nplt.show()\n\nprint(\"\\nClassification Report:\\n\")\nprint(classification_report(y_true, y_pred, target_names=['Healthy', 'Sick']))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-20T20:24:43.500179Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-20T20:24:43.500990Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-20T20:25:08.920077Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-20T20:24:43.500960Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-20T20:25:08.919143Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Generating evaluation metrics for phase 1\n\u001b[1m241/241\u001b[0m \u001b[32m━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\u001b[0m\u001b[37m\u001b[0m \u001b[1m24s\u001b[0m 76ms/step\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 2000x600 with 4 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"name":"stdout","text":"\nClassification Report:\n\n              precision    recall  f1-score   support\n\n     Healthy       1.00      0.99      0.99      3843\n        Sick       0.99      1.00      0.99      3843\n\n    accuracy                           0.99      7686\n   macro avg       0.99      0.99      0.99      7686\nweighted avg       0.99      0.99      0.99      7686\n\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":8},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 4. Phase 2: Multi-Class Classification (Disease Stage)\nNow that the model can detect the presence of Alzheimer's, building of a \"Specialist\" model. We filter the dataset to only include sick patients and attempt to classify the severity of the disease (Very Mild, Mild, Moderate). We will balance these three classes to prevent majority class bias.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"print(\"Preparation of balanced dataset for phase 2 (sick patients only)\")\n\n# Create a copy of the dataset containing only the patients classified as sick\nsick_only_df = df[df['binary'] == 'Sick'].copy()\n\n# Find the smallest number of images among the 3 sickness stages\nmin_count = sick_only_df['stage'].value_counts().min()\nprint(f\"Balancing classes to {min_count} images per stage\")\n\n# Undersampling : take exactly \"min_count\" images for each of the 3 stages\n# to ensures a perfectly balanced dataset (33% moderate, 33% mild, 33% very mild)\nbalanced_stage_df = sick_only_df.groupby('stage').sample(n=min_count, random_state=42)\n\n# Shuffle the new balanced dataset\nbalanced_stage_df = balanced_stage_df.sample(frac=1, random_state=42).reset_index(drop=True)\n\n# Split into training (80%) and testing (20%) sets, keeping the exact same stage proportions (stratify)\ntrain_stage_df, test_stage_df = train_test_split(balanced_stage_df, test_size=0.2, random_state=42, stratify=balanced_stage_df['stage'])\n\ndatagen_stage = ImageDataGenerator()\n\n# Load training images\ntrain_gen_stage = datagen_stage.flow_from_dataframe(\n    dataframe=train_stage_df, x_col='path', y_col='stage',\n    target_size=(128, 128), batch_size=32, class_mode='categorical', validate_filenames=False\n)\n\n# Load testing images\ntest_gen_stage = datagen_stage.flow_from_dataframe(\n    dataframe=test_stage_df, x_col='path', y_col='stage',\n    target_size=(128, 128), batch_size=32, class_mode='categorical', shuffle=False, validate_filenames=False\n)\n\nprint(\"\\nBuilding phase 2 model\")\n\n# Load an another EfficientNetB0 (we don't reuse the phase 1 model to avoid transferring its binary bias)\nbase_model_stage = EfficientNetB0(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(128, 128, 3))\nbase_model_stage.trainable = True\n\n# Freeze most of the network, leave only the last 20 layers open for medical fine-tuning\nfor layer in base_model_stage.layers[:-20]: \n    layer.trainable = False\n\nmodel_stage = Sequential([\n    base_model_stage,\n    GlobalAveragePooling2D(),\n    BatchNormalization(),\n    Dropout(0.5),\n    # difference : we use 3 neurons (for 3 stages) and 'softmax' activation\n    # \"softmax\" ensures all 3 output probabilities sum up to exactly 100%\n    Dense(3, activation='softmax') # 3 classes\n])\n\n# Compile the model, we use \"categorical_crossentropy\" because we have more than 2 classes\nmodel_stage.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=1e-4), loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])\n\nprint(\"Starting training of phase 2\")\nhistory_stage = model_stage.fit(\n    train_gen_stage,\n    epochs=15, # We allow a more epochs (15) because multi-class is a harder task\n    validation_data=test_gen_stage,\n    callbacks=[EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=5, restore_best_weights=True), \n               ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', factor=0.5, patience=3)]\n)\nprint(\"Phase 2 training complete\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-20T20:30:54.702691Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-20T20:30:54.703378Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-20T20:32:22.113485Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-20T20:30:54.703347Z","shell